# Contributing to {{package_name}}

Thank you for considering contributing to `{{package_name}}`! We welcome contributions of all kinds, including bug fixes, new features, documentation improvements, and more.

## Getting Started

1. **Fork the Repository**: Start by forking the repository to your GitHub account.
2. **Clone the Repository**: Clone your forked repository to your local machine.
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/{{package_name}}.git
   ```
3. **Set Up the Environment**:
   ```bash
   uv sync
   ```
4. **Run Tests**: Ensure everything is working:
   ```bash
   just test
   ```

## Development Commands

All development tasks use [just](https://github.com/casey/just) as the command runner:

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `just test` | Run pytest test suite |
| `just lint` | Check code with ruff |
| `just format` | Format code with ruff |
| `just fix` | Auto-fix lint issues |
| `just install` | Install dependencies (`uv sync`) |
| `just clean` | Remove generated files |
| `just demo` | Launch Streamlit demo |

Run `just` with no arguments to see all available commands.

## Making Changes

1. **Create a Branch**: Create a new branch for your changes.
   ```bash
   git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
   ```
2. **Make Your Changes**: Follow the coding standards in `CLAUDE.md`.
3. **Run Quality Checks**:
   ```bash
   just lint
   just format
   just test
   ```
4. **Update Documentation**: If your changes affect the public API or user-facing functionality, update the relevant documentation in `docs/`.
5. **Update CHANGELOG.md**: Add an entry under `[Unreleased]` section:

        **Feature/Fix Name**: Brief description of the change (#PR_NUMBER)

## Before Committing

1. `just lint` - fix any errors
2. `just format` - format code
3. `just test` - ensure tests pass
4. Update `CHANGELOG.md` under `[Unreleased]`

## Submitting Changes

1. **Commit Your Changes**: Write clear and concise commit messages.
   ```bash
   git add .
   git commit -m "Add feature: your-feature-name"
   ```
2. **Push to Your Fork**: Push your changes to your forked repository.
   ```bash
   git push origin feature/your-feature-name
   ```
3. **Open a Pull Request**: Open a pull request to the `main` branch of the original repository. Include a clear description of your changes and reference any related issues.

## Release Notes

Every pull request must include a release notes entry in `CHANGELOG.md` under the `[Unreleased]` section:

- Use categories: `Added`, `Changed`, `Fixed`, `Security`, `Deprecated`, `Removed`
- Format: `- **Feature/Fix Name**: Brief description (#PR_NUMBER)`
- Make entries user-focused, not implementation details

## Need Help?

If you have any questions or need assistance, feel free to open an issue or reach out to the maintainers.